         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">21/3/88. ¶  ¶ How inexpressibly sad, dear Mr Crawford, the tragical fate of your poor brother. ¶  To see a young life pass away, when most of its hopes seemed yet before it, always is particularly mou...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">88.03.21</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alexander Crawford</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Archives, University of New England, Armidale, NSW.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/3/88.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>How inexpressibly sad, dear Mr Crawford, the tragical fate of your poor brother.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Richard Crawford fractured his skull when thrown from his horse (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Armidale express and New England general advertiser, </seg>
                     <seg style="">2 March 1888, p. </seg>4).</p>
               </note> To see a young life pass away, when most of its hopes seemed yet before it, always is particularly mournful. On more than one occasion in my many years travels I narrowly escaped a fate, similar to that of your poor brother I am quite touched with your persevering kindness towards me, even in your mournful sadness. What splendid observations in entirely new regions <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               </seg> would carry on in Central Australia!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Pray do not go out <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">purposely</hi>
               </seg> for anything, about which I might have written, as it would not be right to tax your time and your resources.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>41 <name key="Mentha%20saturejoides">Mentha saturejoides</name> RBrown</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>40 Eryngium!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Possibly a reduced form of E. rostratum (Cavanilles); but I never saw anything like it before. It wood<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">would?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> need specimens in seeds, to determine the precise position of this plant in the bot system.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>39 <name key="Agrostis">Agrostis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>42 <name key="Eucalyptus%20obliqua">Eucalyptus obliqua</name> (l'Heritière)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A new and far northern locality for this stringybark-tree. I shall record under your name the usefulness of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">resin</hi>
               </seg> of Euc. maculata for varnish. I find it will in that form, when applied and dried resist water.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B88.12.01, p. 154, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eucalyptus%20maculata">Eucalyptus maculata</name>
                     </seg>, 'The kino of this species is quite resinous, so much so that articles varnished with it withstand the application of watery fluids (A. R. Crawford).'</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The text ends, without valediction, at the bottom of the fourth and final page on the sheet. It is possible that the letter continued on another sheet, now lost.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
